Yes, the steps I outlined are for creating an adapter for your RecyclerView that can display images. You can create a separate adapter class that extends RecyclerView.Adapter<MyViewHolder> and contains the above methods:

```kotlin
class MyAdapter(private val imageLocations: List<String>) : RecyclerView.Adapter<MyViewHolder>() {
    override fun onCreateViewHolder(parent: ViewGroup, viewType: Int): MyViewHolder {
        // Inflate the layout for the RecyclerView item
        val itemView = LayoutInflater.from(parent.context)
           .inflate(R.layout.recycler_view_item, parent, false)
        return MyViewHolder(itemView)
    }

    override fun onBindViewHolder(holder: MyViewHolder, position: Int) {
        // Load the image at the specified location and set it to the ImageView
        val imageFile = File(imageLocations[position])
        val bitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(imageFile.path)
        holder.imageView.setImageBitmap(bitmap)
    }

    override fun getItemCount(): Int {
        // Return the number of items in the RecyclerView
        return imageLocations.size
    }
}
```
Then, you can create an instance of this adapter and set it to your RecyclerView:

```kotlin
val adapter = MyAdapter(imageLocations)
recyclerView.adapter = adapter
```

Make sure to replace `MyViewHolder` with your actual ViewHolder class name and `recycler_view_item` with the name of your layout file for the RecyclerView item.

To show the full-screen image when the user taps an image in your `RecyclerView`, you can add an `OnClickListener` to each `ImageView` in your `MyViewHolder` class. Here's an example implementation:

1. Define a `ClickListener` interface in your adapter class that you'll use to notify the activity or fragment when an image is clicked:

   ```kotlin
   interface ClickListener {
       fun onClick(position: Int)
   }
   ```

2. Add a `ClickListener` variable to your `MyAdapter` class that you can set from your activity or fragment:

   ```kotlin
   var clickListener: ClickListener? = null
   ```

3. Modify your `MyViewHolder` class to add an `OnClickListener` to the `imageView`:

   ```kotlin
   class MyViewHolder(itemView: View) : RecyclerView.ViewHolder(itemView) {
       val imageView: ImageView = itemView.findViewById(R.id.imageView)

       init {
           // Add an OnClickListener to the imageView to handle clicks
           imageView.setOnClickListener {
               // Notify the adapter's click listener interface about the click event
               clickListener?.onClick(adapterPosition)
           }
       }
   }
   ```

4. In your activity or fragment, set the click listener for the adapter and implement the `onClick()` method to show the full-screen image:

   ```kotlin
   adapter.clickListener = object : MyAdapter.ClickListener {
       override fun onClick(position: Int) {
           val imageFile = File(imageLocations[position])
           val bitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeFile(imageFile.path)
           val intent = Intent(this@MyActivity, FullScreenImageActivity::class.java)
           intent.putExtra("image", bitmap)
           startActivity(intent)
       }
   }
   ```

   Note that FullScreenImageActivity is a separate activity that you have to create. It should display the image in full-screen mode and have a way for the user to dismiss it.

When the user clicks any image in the `RecyclerView`, the `MyViewHolder`'s `OnClickListener` will be triggered, which in turn calls the interface's `onClick()` method and passes the clicked position. Your activity or fragment, which implements the `ClickListener` interface, will then retrieve the image bitmap at the clicked position, create an intent to launch the FullScreenImageActivity, and pass the bitmap in the intent as an extra. Once the FullScreenImageActivity is launched, it will display the bitmap in full-screen mode.

