To add a context menu to your `RecyclerView` item that allows the user to delete an image, you can follow these steps:

1. In your `MyViewHolder` class, add a long-press listener to the `imageView` that displays a context menu when triggered:

   ```kotlin
   class MyViewHolder(itemView: View) : RecyclerView.ViewHolder(itemView), View.OnCreateContextMenuListener {
       val imageView: ImageView = itemView.findViewById(R.id.imageView)

       init {
           // Add the context menu listener to the imageView
           imageView.setOnCreateContextMenuListener(this)
       }

       override fun onCreateContextMenu(
           menu: ContextMenu?,
           v: View?,
           menuInfo: ContextMenu.ContextMenuInfo?
       ) {
           // Inflate the context menu
           menuInflater.inflate(R.menu.context_menu, menu)

           // Set the menu title to the clicked image's file name
           menu?.setHeaderTitle(File(imageLocations[adapterPosition]).name)

           // Add a delete menu item
           menu?.add(Menu.NONE, R.id.action_delete, Menu.NONE, "Delete")
       }
   }
   ```

   In this code, you're implementing the `View.OnCreateContextMenuListener` interface and adding a long-press listener to the `ImageView`. When the listener is triggered, the `onCreateContextMenu()` method is called, which inflates a context menu and adds a delete menu item to it.

2. Define the `R.menu.context_menu` resource file for your context menu:

   ```xml
   <menu xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android">
       <header android:id="@+id/header" />

       <item android:id="@+id/action_delete"
             android:title="Delete" />
   </menu>
   ```

3. In your `MyActivity` or `MyFragment`, implement the `OnCreateContextMenuListener` interface and override the `onContextItemSelected()` method to handle the delete menu item selection:

   ```kotlin
   class MyActivity : AppCompatActivity(), MyAdapter.ClickListener, View.OnCreateContextMenuListener {

       // ...

       override fun onCreateContextMenu(
           menu: ContextMenu,
           view: View,
           menuInfo: ContextMenu.ContextMenuInfo?
       ) {
           val inflater: MenuInflater = menuInflater
           inflater.inflate(R.menu.context_menu, menu)
       }

       override fun onContextItemSelected(item: MenuItem): Boolean {
           return when (item.itemId) {
               R.id.action_delete -> {
                   // Retrieve the image file at the clicked position
                   val imageFile = File(imageLocations[selectedPosition])

                   // Delete the image file from storage
                   imageFile.delete()

                   // Remove the image from the list and notify the adapter
                   imageLocations.removeAt(selectedPosition)
                   adapter.notifyItemRemoved(selectedPosition)

                   true
               }
               else -> super.onContextItemSelected(item)
           }
       }
   }
   ```

   In this code, you're implementing the `OnCreateContextMenuListener` interface and overriding the `onContextItemSelected()` method, which is called when the user selects a menu item in the context menu. If the user selects the delete menu item, you retrieve the image file at the clicked position, delete it from your storage, remove the image from the list of files and update the adapter.

   Note that you need to keep track of the clicked position using a `selectedPosition` member variable in your activity or fragment class before you display the context menu.

4. Finally, you need to register the long-press listener on the `ImageView` by calling `registerForContextMenu()` in your `MyActivity` or `MyFragment`:

   ```kotlin
   override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
       // ...
       recyclerView.setOnCreateContextMenuListener(this@MyActivity)
       registerForContextMenu(recyclerView)
   }
   ```

That's it! Now, the user can long-press an image in your `RecyclerView` to display a context menu with a delete option. If they choose to delete the image, it will be removed from your storage and the `RecyclerView` will be updated to reflect the change.

